            <p>UNITED STATES NATIONAL MUSEUM<lb/>
                UNDER DIRECTION OF<lb/>
                THE SMITHSONIAN INSTITUTION<lb/></p>
            <p>WASHINGTON<lb/>
                July 19<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1892<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. Dr. S. Morais<lb/>
                546 N. 5th St. Philadelphia Pa.<lb/></p>
            <p>Dear Doctor Morais<lb/></p>
            <p>You are aware I presume<lb/> that there now exists at the National<lb/> Museum the nucleus of a collection of Jewish<lb/> Ceremonial objects.  I am very anxious to develop<lb/> this collection in view of the approach of<lb/> the Worlds Columbian Exposition&#44; as it is not<lb/> unlikely that the Smithsonian Institution will<lb/> make an exhibit there of objects of religious<lb/> ceremony.<lb/></p>
            <p>Do you think that the Mickveh<lb/> Israel Congregation has any objects to spare<lb/> that could be borrowed for such a<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>purpose.  It is my idea that we might<lb/> at the same time make a creditable show&#45;<lb/>ing of Jewish ecclesiastical art.<lb/></p>
            <p>It is needless to say that the<lb/> utmost care would be taken of these objects<lb/> that they would be worthily installed and<lb/> would be exhibited in the name of the<lb/> Synagogue.<lb/>  Very Sincerely Yours<lb/> Cyrus Adler<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
